# Example HTTP Runbook

This file demonstrates the syntax and features of Neon Playbook for VS Code.

# Global variables - defined at the top, available to all requests
@baseUrl = https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com
@userId = 1

### Get a Single Post
# Simple GET request with variable interpolation
GET {{baseUrl}}/posts/{{userId}}
Accept: application/json

### Create a New Post
# POST request with JSON body
POST {{baseUrl}}/posts
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "title": "My New Post",
  "body": "This is the content of my post",
  "userId": {{userId}}
}

# Capture the ID of the newly created post
@newPostId = res.data.id
> debug(@newPostId)

### Get the Created Post
# Use the captured ID from the previous request
GET {{baseUrl}}/posts/{{newPostId}}
Accept: application/json

### Update the Post
# PATCH request to update fields
PATCH {{baseUrl}}/posts/{{newPostId}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "title": "Updated Title"
}

### Delete the Post
# DELETE request
DELETE {{baseUrl}}/posts/{{newPostId}}

### Example with Line Continuation
# You can split long URLs across multiple lines using backslash
GET {{baseUrl}}/posts\
    ?userId={{userId}}\
    &_limit=5
Accept: application/json

### Example with Multiple Headers
GET {{baseUrl}}/posts/1
Accept: application/json
Cache-Control: no-cache
User-Agent: Neon-Playbook/1.0

---

## Authentication Example

# This example shows a typical login + authenticated request flow

@authUrl = https://reqres.in/api

### Login Request
POST {{authUrl}}/login
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "email": "eve.holt@reqres.in",
  "password": "cityslicka"
}

@authToken = res.data.token
> debug(@authToken)

### Get Users with Auth Token
GET {{authUrl}}/users?page=1
Authorization: Bearer {{authToken}}
Accept: application/json

@firstUserId = res.data.data[0].id
> debug(@firstUserId)

### Get Specific User
GET {{authUrl}}/users/{{firstUserId}}
Authorization: Bearer {{authToken}}
Accept: application/json
